                        <br>

                        <p>BIGO data processing is organized in three different phases, as it can be observed in the figure above.</p>
                        
                        <p>The output of the first phase consists of a set of gene enrichment analysis results. There are two different options to achieve it. In the first option, users are able to generate a gene enrichment analysis result providing a group of genes, either using a file per group or including all of them in a single file.  BIGO uses <a href="http://compbio.charite.de/contao/index.php" target="_blank">Ontologizer</a> tool to carry out the gene enrichment analysis. As a second option, users provide their own gene enrichment analysis results using a concrete file format.</p>
                        
                        <p>In the second phase, BIGO processes the gene enrichment analysis results in order to generate a biological term ranking. The ascending order of that ranking is based on the number of groups of genes in which every biological term has been detected. In order to generate different ranking results, BIGO offers the possibility of including or excluding biological terms based on filtering tools or users own decisions and modifying the ranking thresholds. This ranking is used as an input for the last phase.</p>

                        <p>In the third phase, BIGO uses the biological terms ranking to infer a groups of genes network. This network, represented as a graph, will show the relationship of the different group of genes in terms of common biological functionalities. Users are able to navigate the graph in order to extract useful information about every generated relationship.</p>
                        
